    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>August 2001: Terror Loomed as America Slept</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Paul Goldstein letter on Apr 11 article holds Pres Bush's Aug 6, 2001, intelligence briefing about terrorist threat should have been made public at time</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Regarding the release of the Aug. 6, 2001, brief (front page, April 11), perhaps the problem is not so much the structural and systemic obstacles that prevented the sharing of information between the F.B.I. and the C.I.A., but rather that none of the information was shared with the general public until now.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Regarding the release of the Aug. 6, 2001, brief (front page, April 11), perhaps the problem is not so much the structural and systemic obstacles that prevented the sharing of information between the F.B.I. and the C.I.A., but rather that none of the information was shared with the general public until now.</p>
        <p>One has to wonder at the possible impact (in terms of public outcry energizing the administration and, more important, the airlines and their employees) if the Aug. 6 briefing had been contemporaneously published on the front page of every major daily newspaper and on the Internet.</p>
        <p>PAUL GOLDSTEIN  Chicago, April 11, 2004</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
